  "original_title": "Sri Lanka military calls for politicians to get their act together, public to be calm",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka military calls for politicians to get their act together, public to be calm",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s military chiefs had asked party leaders to meet with the Parliamentary speaker and tell them next political steps they intended to take until a new President is elected and called on the public and young protestors to be calm, Chief of Staff Shavendra Silva said.",
        "The speaker had said President Rajapaksa will resign later today. The military chiefs had had discussion with the speaker.",
        "\u201cThe heads of the tri-forces and police chief made a request from the speaker to call a meeting of party leaders and clarify the next political steps, and inform us of the political steps,\u201dGeneral Silva said in a televised address flanked by the heads of Air Force, Army, Navy and Police.",
        "\u201cWe expect these decisions to be made public in the evening,\u201d",
        "\u201cUntil the new President is elected we appeal to the public to be calm.\u201d",
        "Sri Lanka\u2019s Prime Minister Ranil Wickremsinghe said earlier in the day that fascist segments among protestors are making trouble while opposition leader Sajith Premadasa also made a rhetoric charged statement while calling for calm.",
        "Ex-President Maithripala Sirisena said the quickest way to calm young protestors was for Ranil Wickremesighe who was appointed acting President to resign."
      ],
